text.tspan: Figure p. Wicklefeature dictionary kernel ridge regression solution, N=1000. The algorithm
calculates the closed form ridge regression solution to present tense verbs (X), and corresponding
past tense verbs (Y) for a set training set size. Instead of streaming to counteract increasing
runtime, this closed form calcuation runtime only changes with dimension N, not with the number
of samples. The size of W is now n by n, where n = size of the training set. We can see perfect
similarity with the training set because W is always able to store n samples. Its lower test
similarities imply that the HD algorithm is biased towards higher similarities by having the
solution update via addition.
Figure q. Legend in bottom right instead.
Figure r. Wickelfeature dictionary online regression solution, N=1000. The model
(W) is an N by N matrix. Our binding rule (XY) is the same as that of closed form regression.
We try to imitate the closed form regularization rule by creating a pseudo-correlation matrix,
which is the inverse of the addition of the identity matrix I and covariance matrix of X. W is still
updated by addition after every sample. This model is basically the regular HD algorithm and
doesn't resemble regression.
Figure s. Wickelfeature dictionary online regression solution, N=1000. The model (W) is
an N by N matrix. Our binding rule (XY) is the same as that of closed form regression. We try to
imitate the closed form regularization rule by creating a different pseudo-correlation matrix,
which is the inverse of the addition of the identity matrix I and covariance matrix of W. Now we
can regularize based on knowledge of prior samples and in a sense include the covariance of the
entire training set rather than only that of one sample. W is still updated by addition after every
sample. This model doesn't do nearly as well on the training set as the least squares or kernel
ridge regression solution. However, training similarity does level off quickly to a somewhat
constant similarity. The test similarity behaves like the closed form solutions and even occurs
around the same similarity values as the closed form solutions. Can we assume W is now
generalizing?
